Review Detail: The absolute most hellish experience I have ever had in my life for trying to deliver packages. No safe place to drop packages in a common area. No access to building. Dial 955 to get office access at panel, then spend the next ten minutes hunting around with NO DIRECTIONAL SIGNAGE AT INTERSECTIONS to find a unit number. Unbelievably frustrating and I never want to have to come back here again!! update: Yeah, I hear your reply. I'm not joking about the lack of signage, though. In the big open courtyards, there's a number of 4-way intersections where there's absolutely no signage saying which is where - and not even a sign within reasonable distance of any direction. So you just have to walk, look for a number, look for another number, judge if it's going up or down, turn around, try a different intersection... that's what I mean about NO SIGNAGE. There are sparse signs at entryways, but that's about it. Within a courtyard of confusion, nothing. The same delivery guy isn't likely going to go to the same place twice. While I was delivering, every day is a new area, a new route. Can't expect delivery people to know - because almost every delivery is guaranteed to be their first (and last) time, just by how they get dispatched. Not to mention the inability to get around inside, with RFID locked doors every five feet, again having to find other ways around the locked doors, when the office is closed (either for C-19 or just outside business hours)...

Location is 5/5, I'm 15 minutes from everything (except holidays going by fashion valley), and it's close enough to the water that it stays cooler over here in summer than all of my friends places. The apartments themselves are pretty decent, newly redone bathrooms and kitchens, the rest is ok. They are ok with paint/ decorating and I've really been able to make it my own. Inside courtyard location is great, I feel like I'm in a park, not on a busy street. Parking in my area is never an issue, and I appreciate the generously wide spots. The parking feels safe, there's lots of lighting and its good enough to keep Jaguars and Maseratis in so that's a good sign. There are brand new lighted carports available too. Electric/Plug in hybrid parking and charging provided. Leasing process was simple, so was signing my renewal. I haven't used the amenities much, but there's a beautiful heated pool, hot tub, tennis, gym, vending machine, small meeting room with wifi, dig runs, I think a putting green, and nice grills with seating and firepits. I don't have a dog, but there are dogs all over here, owners/landscapers are very good with cleanup up poop, I've never seen any. Landscaping in general seems a cut above. Lots of flowers that attract hummingbirds. Maintenance requests done online the night before are completed when I get home from work. Central air, individual washers and dryers in every unit. The office team is fabulous, especially my girl Lauren and the boss lady Simona in management. Community feel too, I dont feel like just a number, I'm a person too. Happy to be home??
Latest Response: Thank you for the amazing review, Brad! We appreciate you taking the time to let us know how much you're enjoying your home and that you were able to make it your own. We all love being near the water, especially as things heat up for the summer! Our team strives to keep the grounds in stellar shape and will be grateful that you've noticed their hard work. We're very fortunate to have Lauren and all of the team members to keep CentrePointe a step above the rest, as they all work hard to meet our residents needs and expectations. If you need anything at all, please reach out to us and we will be happy to serve you. We appreciate it! -- Simona D., CentrePointe.

Review Detail: This is by far the worst apartment complex I’ve ever lived in. We’ve had problems with them since the day we moved in. On move-in day we called them because there were bees swarming our apartment and they refused to do anything. Over the next few months we started experiencing spiders hanging from the tree in front of our front door. Eventually the spiders were building webs in front of our entrance and we were walking into spider webs daily and when we called to complain they laughed and advised us to carry a broom. After months of this we had to write them a letter and demand that they do something about the spiders. They then came out to our apartment with the current manager at the time and the maintenance supervisor to explain to us that the health of the tree that was over growing into our front door entrance was more important than the health of the residents who were paying rent. They refused to continue to cut back the tree that was blocking our front door they refused to continue to spray to keep the spiders from making webs in front of our door that was blocking our entrance. Ultimately, they refused to provide any assistance and we then had to contact the regional manager to see if they could help us with the situation. After about a week of communication with the regional manager he agreed to let us move into a different unit. The apartments then try to make us pay double rent for occupying apartments at the same time while we were trying to move which is physically impossible to move from one apartment to another without occupying them both. We then had to speak to two different managers from the regional office who finally did the right thing to let us move without being charged. These apartments are over priced, run down, and they are not worth the money or the headache that it causes to live here. The maintenance staff does a poor job of keeping the property, the laundry room constantly has transients in it, and the property itself is rundown, old, and falling apart. A couple weeks after we moved out we received a bill that was attempting to charge us an extra $100 over the deposit we had placed. besides the normal carpet cleaning and apartment cleaning fee; they were attempting to charge us $160 for painting the apartment that had no damage and we had only been there for eight months. When I called and spoke to someone in the office they became nasty and rude with me and hung up in my face. We had to reach out and email the manager and regional managers before this could be resolved. They ended up removing the bogus painting charge because they knew they were wrong. Their invoices are a joke they literally look like something typed up on someone’s computer that anyone could’ve created. This apartment was nothing but a headache from beginning to end and I can truly say I regret ever setting my sights on the Esplanade apartments. I strongly advise anyone who cares about being happy in their home to never rent from the Esplanade.

Tore up our closet and our floor and had contractors entering into our apartment while both myself and infant son were sick with the flu at the time. - Towed multiple family members cars, even though there is a sticker system, which did not go on any of my family's cars. Fought to get refunds and only received half each time. - Lack of response on emails and returning phone calls, and sometimes just plain rudeness on the phone. Most recent example: Sent an email about moving out and scheduling a walkthrough on Friday April, 3rd. No response and no follow up, even after sending a second email on Sunday April, 5th. Called in, spoke to Nancy, and when I asked if they saw the email, her response was "not sure, just tell me what the email said." - Lastly, I have a whole email that I sent to customer care that I sent on July, 2017, listing out all of the complaints I had up until that time. It has been frustrating to live there to say the least, and I couldn't be any happier leaving. The community, the neighbors, amenities, and the apartment itself were great. I can't say the same goes for the management team there.

Review Detail: This is by far the worst apartment complex I’ve ever lived in. We’ve had problems with them since the day we moved in. Over the next few months we started experiencing spiders hanging from the tree in front of our front door. Eventually the spiders were building webs in front of our entrance and we were walking into spider webs daily and when we called to complain they laughed and advised us to carry a broom. Eventually we had to write them a letter and demand that they do something about the spiders. They then came out to our apartment with the current manager at the time and the maintenance supervisor to explain to us that the health of the tree that was over growing into our front door entrance was more important than the health of the residents who were paying rent. Ultimately, they refused to provide any assistance and we then had to contact the regional manager to see if they could help us with the situation. The apartments then tried to make us pay double rent for occupying apartments at the same time while we were trying to move which is physically impossible to move from one apartment to another without occupying them both. We then had to speak to two different managers from the regional office who finally did the right thing to let us move without being charged. These apartments are expensive, they are run down, and they are not worth the money or the headache that it causes to live here. A couple weeks after we moved out we received a bill that was attempting to charge us an extra $100 over the deposit we had placed. besides the normal carpet cleaning and apartment cleaning fee; they were attempting to charge us $160 for painting the apartment that had no damage and we had only been there for eight months. When I called and spoke to someone in the office they became nasty and rude with me and hung up in my face. We had to reach out and email the manager and regional managers before this could be resolved. They ended up removing the bogus painting charge because they knew they were wrong. Their invoices are a joke they literally look like something typed up on someone’s computer that anyone could’ve created. This apartment was nothing but a headache from beginning to end and I can truly say I regret ever setting my sights on the Esplanade apartments. I strongly advise anyone who cares about being happy in their home to never rent from the Esplanade.

I can never get maintenance. They always want me to submit online. But the rentcafe doesn’t work. It won’t take my email name. So they won’t let me submit requests on the phone. But the rentcafe is flawed. Takes calls to corporate office to get things done. They are not user friendly.

Review Detail: My steps slow down just a tad as I glance down at Pinnacle's beautiful yet homey courtyard from the 3rd story walkway. I lean over the railing to look at Amerige Avenue and the stretch of historical buildings, streets and lush green that make up the unique culture of Downtown Fullerton. Lately I find myself doing these more often while thinking, "Man... I am going to miss living here." Pinnacle at Fullerton is, by far, my #1 favorite place to live. That statement comes with an annotation that I had lived in Upper East Side of Manhattan, New York and in the desirable town of Edgewater, NJ along the Hudson River. Pinnacle at Fullerton offers combination of comfort, convenience and excellent customer service. Personally, I think the layout and design is absolutely gorgeous and well-thought out here - it makes you feel comfortable and cozy like it's your home and you're proud to call it home because everything here is so pleasant to look at. I never had an issue with noisy neighbor or pet remains lying around on the property. Pinnacle at Fullerton is located in the heart of Downtown Fullerton. There is countless number of coffee shops, restaurants, bars, hair salons, yoga studio, bookstore within walking distance. Not to mention museums, Fullerton train station and Fullerton College. Sprouts, Costco, Target, Walmart and Hwy 91 is just 5 minutes away, and getting on the Hwy 91 will take you to Hwy 5 and Hwy 57 in no time. The property is maintained meticulously by Tony and his team. Tony is always friendly and professional. I made 2 requests while living here, and both times Tony completed the work orders the same day I requested, with nothing but smiles and great attitude. Sara, the property manager, is very warm, empathetic and helpful - She always made me feel appreciated as her resident, even after I signed my lease and moved in. I know there are some managers who will look at you only as a dollar sign. Sara always went above and beyond with her service, and that's very rare these days. There is no such thing as perfect apartment community, but I truly believe Pinnacle at Fullerton comes very close to it. I am very sorry that I have to leave Pinnacle at Fullerton for work in another state. If I ever move back to Orange County, I'd definitely live at Pinnacle at Fullerton again. Thank you Sara and Tony. You guys are awesome !!
Latest Response: We can't thank you enough for the glowing review, Joseph. We're honored to rank at the top of your enviable list of past living experiences, and we absolutely love your description of our community! Thank you for the kind words on our property design, aesthetics and property upkeep, and please know that Tony and I truly appreciate the individual recognition. While we hate to see you go, we certainly understand the need to go wherever work takes you, and we wish you the best in your future endeavors! -- Sara G., Pinnacle at Fullerton.

Review Detail: Friendly and helpful management. Responsive to issues. Safety became a concern with the homeless and random people on 3rd/4th street. There were 2 separate occasions where someone tried to enter our apartment, and then pretended that they had the wrong address when they opened the door and they realised that we were home. But I appreciate the steps the management were taking to ramp up the security at the gates. I also found 2 homeless people sleeping by my car one morning. And then there is the homeless person that walks up and down the street yelling 'F**K' at 0500... non of which is the building's issue, but if I had to give negative feedback it would be related to the overall feeling of safety. But I would definitely recommend this building to a friend, despite these issues. It was modern, spacious. had assigned covered parking and in the heart of downtown, and was affordable. Thanks San Fernando. We were truly sad to say goodbye.

Review Detail: Absolutely no cell reception inside apartment. We have to enable WiFi calling, and heaven forbid there’s an emergency between the exterior of the building and our front door, I would not be able to dial 911. Excessive dog barking on neighbors patio. They frequently leave the dog out there for extended periods of time. We’ve contacted office staff via phone and email and had mixed results. One email to the manager was never responded to. All amenities closed during pandemic is smart and appreciated, however I’m still paying the exact same rent which includes the benefit of those amenities. A temporary rent reduction would be appreciated. Garbage room on first floor near the garage entrance is gross. Other residents don’t bother to open the garbage bin, but instead throw garbage bags on top of garbage can or on the floor. Fire alarm frequently goes off and needs servicing and testing. Parking garage gate doesn’t fully open on one side so when two cars are coming and going it’s very tight. There’s plenty of things that we do appreciate and enjoy about the community, but these are the reasons we think about moving elsewhere.

Review Detail: We lived at SP for 2 years and during that time we had our car broken into, which was parked inside the gated garage, within the gated community. Also, our neighbor had his car broken into too. Not to mention the numerous false fire alarms at all times during the night and day! Yes, the landscaping is beautiful and the amenities are awesome but good luck getting your deposit back. Out of $600, we only received $74 back! For a 2 BEDROOM apt, you'll receive only 1 FREE parking, we paid $250 each month plus the annually rent increase!. Because we have 3 cars. The have free parking outside the gate but good luck finding a spot! I contacted management so many times about vehicles being parked in the same spot for weeks or months and nothing was done. I've seen non-residents park their vehicles and then get into another car. We left that apartment in move in condition. The carpet was already matted to begin with, it only needed to be cleaned in the high traffic areas, touch up paint in some areas and replace one of slates of the blinds. They sent me a itemized receipt but all the numbers didn't match. For example, they sent me a copy of a receipt for $400 for painting but the itemized receipt was only $178 for painting.

Review Detail: We moved to this community exactly two months ago and every aspect of our experience has been pleasant and friendly. The staff at the leasing office is welcoming and understanding, even when I had to bring up an uncomfortable issue during the leasing process that ended up being just a small misunderstanding. Neither the office manager nor the office staff lost their professionalism and were able to explain the situation to us in a friendly way. Rachel helped us with our lease, paperwork, and all aspects of our moving experience. She demonstrated professionalism at its best, all the time. Rachel is a valuable asset for Essex and she is key to many of our excellent reviews! Rachel is very kind, understanding, and knowledgeable in her field. After living here for two months I can say it's a very quiet place, well taken care of, and they have an amazing custodial staff that takes almost no time in fixing anything that may be needed. Honestly, we have not found anything wrong with living here. Some of the inconveniences that the parking has, as mentioned by some of the reviews, is nothing compared with the quality of service and living in a nice and clean community. Although parking has never been an issue for us because we always find parking, we are so grateful we don't have to park outside a very busy street or unsafe neighborhood like the one where we moved from. Compared to the other side of the mountain, parking at Meadowood Apartments is heavenly! :) To put the icing on the cake, just this afternoon, I received a call from Christina asking how my husband and I were doing during these troubling times. I was surprised and grateful at the same time. No one, in any of the places I have lived before, had ever taken the time to call us and check in on us. Not even when we faced earthquakes! Thank you Meadowood Apartments, we are very happy tenants and we are grateful for the opportunity to live here.
Latest Response: Thanks for the two-month update, Ruth! It's great to know that you've had such a positive experience working with our team, and I know that Rachel and Christina truly value the individual recognition. They both do an incredible job on behalf of our residents and we always love to see their attentive service acknowledged. It's wonderful to hear that you've enjoyed such a hassle-free living experience, and we hope you'll let us know if there is anything else we can do for you. -- Sagi A., Meadowood.

Review Detail: A Hidden Gem in Mill Creek After living here for a year, it seems a good time to write a review. This place is absolutely terrific. The both the leasing staff and maintenance team are kind and atten…

A Hidden Gem in Mill Creek After living here for a year, it seems a good time to write a review. This place is absolutely terrific. The both the leasing staff and maintenance team are kind and attentive, especially the Community Manager Verita. We had a couple of paperwork bumps when we initially moved in but Verita personally stepped in and made every effort to ensure our move in was as smooth as possible and she has helped us with every need. Both the leasing team and maintenance are active seven days of the week; quite a welcome surprise for a relatively small community! The complex itself is not a gated community, but for all intents and purposes, it might as well be! Tucked into the hill, it is surrounded on two sides by greenery, the side facing Bothell-Everett Highway is completely fenced off, so the only access is from 164th. There's never any outside foot traffic and the local residents for the most part are quiet and friendly! They even have a contract with a security patrol company that sends a marked vehicle every so often to scope out the property, and though their appearance is welcome, I've never felt that they were necessary as I have never felt safer in a community! The rent is quite competitive for the area, though the pet fees are a bit high. There are amenities such as a basketball court, a pool, a small gym, a business centre, and a playground, though much of that is off limits amidst the current pandemic. There is somewhat sufficient open parking with carports (but no garages) available for rent at a reasonable fee. As far as I am aware, all units include washers and dryers (a big requirement for me), balconies, and fireplaces. When we moved in, the community was in the middle of unit renovations one by one with fresh paint, flooring, countertops, cabinets, and new appliances. At the time, we got to choose between a pre- and post- renovated unit with a small difference in rent rate, and the newly renovated units blew our expectations away. The community also recently received a fresh exterior paint job that looks terrific. Overall, we couldn't be happier to call this place home and hope to stay here for many more years to come. The location is terrific, the gated-property feel is exceptional, and the staff are fantastic to work with. A quiet, quaint community to call home.

Review Detail: We have lived here for 3 years and our rent keeps going up as the property value continually decreases. Our rent has increased every year but there have been no updates, upgrades, or changes to our unit. There are so many issues with the condition of the apartment. The appliances and hardware look like they are all still the original outfitting from the 70s. Electrical outlets are loose &/or don’t have power. Refrigerator fan is broken and keeps freezing up and then leaking water, and we’ve had maintenance come and check it twice now, the second time we were told that there was nothing they could do short of replacing the whole fridge but that wouldn’t happen unless it stopped working altogether. So our options are either keep trying to capture the leaking condensation because the fan is not regulating properly, or wait until the fridge stops working altogether and our food spoils. Great. Furthermore, doors and cabinet doors are ajar because they are old af and won’t latch or stay closed. We’ve already had maintenance come and “address” this issue in the past too but it is still happening because the whole building structure is old and crumbling apart as is everything inside the units as well. The cheap ass laminated counter tops started cracking a year after we moved in, the same time the walls and the ceiling starting cracking apart after the rains and buildings settled. Oh yea, and the solution to that was to just fill the half inch structural crack in with caulk. Cool. When we put in a maintenance request to fix the countertops we were told that they would not be able to repair the cracked/chipped portion, only replace the whole thing, and to do that we would need to vacate the apartment for 48 hours, which is ridiculous because we don’t have another place to live in the meantime. So now we just live with a growing patch in the middle of the countertop like a bunch of crackheads. The icing on the proverbial cake was last month when there was a sewer line eruption in the flower bed right in front of our apartment entrance stairs, complete with turds and toilet paper floating down the sidewalk. Once they capped it off they just left the shit and TP to dry on the sidewalk and when we requested a cleanup we were told by the front office that it is technically the city’s job. What? You all just keep slapping bandaids on shit and then act like you’re so benevolent because you installed some new lights or applied a shitty ass paint job. Like wtf even was that? I’ve never seen a worse paint job in my life. You want to keep taking our money and expect us to keep paying even in the middle of a global pandemic but you give us no incentive to stay and keep paying more while the property continues to deteriorate and every time we ask for a an actual repair or solution all we get is excuses why it can’t be done or some half-ass coverup that just falls apart a few weeks or months later. So yea, I’d say our experience living here has been disappointing and frustrating to say the least. There have been domestic disturbances, bloody altercations, and disruptive neighbors that only worsens with each new move-in. We haven’t been able to use the pool or gym area in 2 years because it’s always overrun by shitty ass kids running around like a bunch of lawless animals &/or loud drunken parties. There’s constantly trash and litter defacing the property, not to mention the actual trash receptacle areas are always a disaster. And we had an infestation of roaches a couple months ago because our previous downstairs neighbors were disgusting slobs. I realize you can’t control everybody’s actions but it has become abundantly apparent that the quality of tenants that have moved in within the time we have lived here has declined significantly and that is a direct relation to the quality of ownership and management of the property itself.

Review Detail: People are quick to point out how tight the parking is, but forget all the good qualities about Carmel Landing. I have lived here with my husband for 2 years now, and it was our first apartment after…

People are quick to point out how tight the parking is, but forget all the good qualities about Carmel Landing. I have lived here with my husband for 2 years now, and it was our first apartment after we got married. Boy are we spoiled to have gotten to live in Carmel Landing as our first spot. YES the parking is tight, but the office will work with you to try and find a new spot, or offer an alternate solution. Itza, Wendy, Louise, and Zack have all been incredibly helpful over the years, and sometimes I just pop into the office to say hello and see another smiling face. The community is overall very clean, quiet, and respectful. Maintenance is responsive, and kind. The gyms and facilities are truly a great extension of your space when you live in a smaller apartment. The rent didn't increase very much from year to year and this location allowed us to explore so many parks, local restaurants, and new areas. For us it was more than just a house, it truly became our little home, where we had neighbors over for wine, talked with all the community staff and maintenance workers, and truly enjoyed feeling like part of a community. We're sad to be leaving soon, but thankful for all the positive experiences we've had here. My advice for people apartment shopping is to remember who typically writes reviews. A lot of people will quickly write about one or two bad experiences, or will leave a review if they were "blown away", but often the "content" don't leave as many reviews. This community has less stars than it deserves, and if you have lingering questions ask the front office- they are very transparent. I hope this helped guide your decision!

Review Detail: I've been living at the Fountains at Rivier Oaks for about 1.5 years, and this has been a great home considering the rent in the Bay Area. If you are looking for a fancy resort-like complex, then this is not a place for you. For a relatively lower rent, you get a good size unit with some patio space, a garage space, and a decent size pool and workout room. The management team has been very responsive every time I had an issue, and the maintenance person is super friendly and he fixed any issues with my apartment very smoothly. I have a separate AC/Heating unit for bedroom and the livingroom which has been helpful in saving costs. Considering the high rent in the area, I think the Fountains at River Oaks offers a great value. It's close to highways, shopping areas, and it's very quiet here. I have no one living below my unit and no one above me - this is a rare find for an apartment.

Review Detail: A few positives: You can go monthly if needed. Alfonso who runs maintenance for the entire complex is stellar. Most of the neighbors we'd encountered are friendly. Now the negatives, of which there are many. This property was once managed by another management company before it was taken over by Essex. Every single resident we have talked to over the 15 months we were there liked the previous management company better. That speaks volumes. If you're spending $3000 - $4000+ per month, you should expect more from a property such as this. With 3 young kids, the number one priority for us was to be in a well-insulated building. I worried about my children making noise for others. I was told repeatedly that noise wasn't an issue, everything was well-insulated, and they almost never get any complaints. This is demonstrably false, not just for me but also for other tenants who told me their stories. I trusted the leasing office, but then day 3 after moving in, we had security called on us. In short, the complaint was from an egocentric neighbor below us who never showed his face or even made an effort to have a cordial conversation in the 15 months we were there. What were our kids doing? Laughing and playing hide-and-seek. Not bouncing a ball. I tried to take the high road and wrote an apology to the tenant, who clearly conflated contrition with obsequiousness. Over the months, he repeatedly scared our kids (who started referring to him as "the angry man") by constantly banging loudly on the ceiling, even when he heard noise from neighboring apartments and not ours. The leasing office never apologized for misleading us as they were clearly concerned with was filling empty vacancies. More proof? The communal fireplaces, used as a selling point and told to me during the tour that they are to be repaired soon, never worked. In fact, they haven't worked for years according to some. The excuse from the leasing office? As soon as they got reports, they started taking bids and then had to shut the project down due to Covid-19. Clearly, the timetable does not back up this claim. Months earlier, they had no issue hiring people to redo landscaping out front and painting concrete into white and black squares to match tile by the door. Naturally, curb appeal to attract new tenants took priority over the concerns of existing tenants. More proof? The pool table had a rip in it...never addressed or repaired. Gym equipment? The grips on the universal were coming off, and the rubber was never replaced, just trimmed off. Swiss ball popped one day? Never replaced. Flooding that occurs inside the stairwell on the first floor by the dog run after a rain? Never remedied. How about VOMIT? One day, someone vomited in one of the elevators. We told someone in the leasing office face-to-face late morning/early afternoon that Saturday. He said they got several calls about it and will address it right away. Vomit stayed there until late Monday morning. Can you imagine the stink it left for nearly 48 hours? I understand that no one is on site except for emergencies on Sunday, but clearly if the lone cleaning person is unable to tend to the mess that Saturday, someone in the leasing office should have. I've had my share of dirty jobs. Leaving that mess there on the floor was unacceptable by any health standards. This is just the tip of the iceberg. I haven't even addressed other safety issues like elevator doors that either won't close (only flinch) or elevators that jerk suddenly up and down right when you get in (at random). Again, never addressed or remedied. How about electronic keypad locks that were installed on every door to make it easier for maintenance to enter units? Safety hazard: try telling someone chasing you down the hall to please wait while you enter a complicated 6-digit code and a check mark before you can go inside. The garage gate also consistently failed and stayed open for days on end at times. I can't speak for all Essex-managed properties, but I can definitely say that you should avoid Emerson Valley Village at all costs.
Latest Response: We're sorry about the challenges you've encountered, Michael, though we always appreciate it when residents take the time to share their concerns with us. We understand your frustration over the noise complaints, and we appreciated you working with us as we followed up on the situation. As you noted, the fireplaces were repaired just before all of our amenities were closed due to the health crisis. Like you, we can't wait to put them to good use. Also, we're pleased to say that our gym equipment has been repaired, and our mechanical issues with our elevator and gates are repaired. We were grateful for everyone's patience and while those fixes were being made, and we'll certainly look into the other issues you mentioned. As always, we hope you'll let us know if there is anything we can do to improve your living experience. Our team is always here to help. Thank you. -- Michael K., Emerson Valley Village.

Review Detail: Omar and his staff has been great throughout the years. Very professional and excellent service provided. Community is under new management so I can’t say much but I could see their willingness to improve the community. Great memories were spent the last few years and my neighbors within the building were great. Just recently, a lot of people parking their work vehicles, big trucks. Parking issues as always. Kids throughout the day and night. And solicitors from two families who are up late at night gathering talking loud, a group of vans parked together.

To start off, the management has gotten a lot better since when we first moved in so we’re grateful for that. We lived in Carmel Landing for 13 months, the #1 complaint we have is the parking. Such a tight squeeze and nothing is ever done when cars are double-parked. Second, We have almost never had a good experience with the leasing office. When moving out I called and asked what we needed for moving out if we needed to fill out any paperwork & I was told no. We just needed to do a pre-move out inspection so I went ahead and booked it. 1 week later I get a call saying we need to book our pre-move out inspection, I told her we already scheduled and she said it wasn’t on the calendar, so we re-booked. Days later I was called again asking from a THIRD employee at the leasing office for our “move out” documents. But we were told we didn’t need to sign any documents. When I received the documents the date was saying we would move out 2021 instead of 2020. It was fixed and we signed. Days later, we were told it was done incorrectly on their end and we needed to re-sign. Over and over again there was issues. After moving out and talking to three different employees I still received phone calls asking for our forwarding address that I have given 4 times now. All said & done, we put in a $1,000 security deposit (pet deposit) and only received back $100... Our advice, save your money and live somewhere else.

Review Detail: I moved to DTLA about 1.5 years ago. Coming from NY state and moving across the country, I really had no clue where was a good area to live in LA. I wanted to be in a place where I could easily meet new people and also have shopping and culture at my doorstep. I came across Bunker Hill Towers Apartments by chance, and I am so happy with my decision to become a resident. DTLA has areas which are unsafe and sketchy, but Bunker Hill Tower Apts and it’s immediate surrounding area is safe and well monitored by security day and night. There is an enormous courtyard within the complex which is mostly separate from the craziness of the street; I have a small dog, and myself, like many other tenants, are able to walk our 4-legged friends at any time of the day. I rented a 1 bedroom, which offered a decent amount of space for inner-city living; it is modern and bright, with floor-to-ceiling windows. Other big perks about the complex are that there is a trusted dog-walker who resides at the complex who came recommended to me, and there is a fabulous corner store/market behind the complex. I enjoyed living here so much that I signed a new lease and upgraded to a 2 bedroom corner apt, which is just as beautiful as the pictures on the website. The leasing office and always accommodating and Monica and Natalie have really gone out of their way to make sure I have been satisfied. Review Detail: Both of my air conditioning units have been broken for over a month now and despite several (we're talking 10+) phone calls back and forth to maintenance and leasing, nothing has been done to fix them. Not only that, but every time I call to follow up on this issue no one seems to even understand or remember what my problem is. I understand we are in a pandemic, but experiencing a completely broken AC system in a home when it's 100+ degrees outside is in breach of the warranty of habitability clause. I have offered to get the air conditioner fixed myself, but have been told I cannot. This is getting absolutely ridiculous. I pay an insane amount of money to live in a place that doesn't have working appliances. Additionally, there are constant package issues with this apartment. They get lost nonstop, are left in front of the leasing office for no apparent reason, and are locked in random post boxes with a seemingly missing key to retrieve them. The walls and floors are paper thin (I can literally hear my upstairs neighbors walking lightly from room to room). And the fire alarms have gone off at least 6 times in the last month for no reason. My cat is now terrified of the TV making noises because she thinks it's an alarm. The one thing I will say is that Rosey in the leasing office is incredibly kind and helpful. I unfortunately haven't been able to work with her through this insane air conditioning issue, but I did really appreciate her help and guidance during the move in process. She's the one saving grace to this place. All in all, I highly recommend you continue your apartment search and skip this place. Unless you want to be sweating nonstop, constantly kicked out of your apt due to alarms, and spend a good chunk of the day listening to your neighbors conversations against your will.

Review Detail: UPDATE - after posting this my air conditioning finally got fixed. Epic has informed me they're going to work on their maintenance/resident communication which is good. Hoping it improves in the future! Both of my air conditioning units have been broken for over a month now and despite several (we're talking 10+) phone calls back and forth to maintenance and leasing, nothing has been done to fix them. Not only that, but every time I call to follow up on this issue no one seems to even understand or remember what my problem is. I understand we are in a pandemic, but experiencing a completely broken AC system in a home when it's 100+ degrees outside is in breach of the warranty of habitability clause. I have offered to get the air conditioner fixed myself, but have been told I cannot. This is getting absolutely ridiculous. I pay an insane amount of money to live in a place that doesn't have working appliances. Additionally, there are constant package issues with this apartment. They get lost nonstop, are left in front of the leasing office for no apparent reason, and are locked in random post boxes with a seemingly missing key to retrieve them. The walls and floors are paper thin (I can literally hear my upstairs neighbors walking lightly from room to room). And the fire alarms have gone off at least 6 times in the last month for no reason. My cat is now terrified of the TV making noises because she thinks it's an alarm. The one thing I will say is that Rosey in the leasing office is incredibly kind and helpful. I unfortunately haven't been able to work with her through this insane air conditioning issue, but I did really appreciate her help and guidance during the move in process. She's the one saving grace to this place. All in all, I highly recommend you continue your apartment search and skip this place. Unless you want to be sweating nonstop, constantly kicked out of your apt due to alarms, and spend a good chunk of the day listening to your neighbors conversations against your will.
